expanded="true"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>12446</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Observation</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-0051</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-0051.xml</fr:route><fr:title>An alternative definition of duploids</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Equivalently, we can define a <fr:link
href="jms-0050.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-0050">duploid</fr:link> to be a <fr:link
href="jms-004T.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004T">univalent</fr:link> <fr:link
href="jms-004F.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004F">preduploid</fr:link> such that every object is <fr:em>merely equipped with</fr:em> both an <fr:link
href="jms-004M.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004M">upshift</fr:link> and a <fr:link
href="jms-004P.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004P">downshift</fr:link>.</fr:p><fr:p>To see that the <fr:link
href="jms-0050.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-0050">main definition</fr:link> implies our alternative definition, let <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> be an object of the preduploid; because we are proving that <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> is <fr:em>merely equipped with</fr:em> both an <fr:link
href="jms-004M.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004M">upshift</fr:link> and a <fr:link
href="jms-004P.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004P">downshift</fr:link>, we may proceed by cases on the <fr:link
href="jms-0045.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-0045">polarization</fr:link> of <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>If <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="jms-004B.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004B">positive</fr:link>, we choose the identity map <fr:tex>A \vdash  A</fr:tex> for the downshift and we use our assumption to deduce that <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> has an upshift.</fr:li>
  <fr:li>If <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="jms-004B.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004B">negative</fr:link>, we choose the identity map <fr:tex>A \vdash  A</fr:tex> for the upshift and we use our assumption to deduce that <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> has a downshift.</fr:li></fr:ol>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>11566</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-0051</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>Conversely, assume that every object is merely equipped with both an upshift and a downshift. That a positive object <fr:tex>P</fr:tex> has an upshift <fr:link
href="jms-004X.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004X">is a proposition</fr:link>, so we can use our assumption that <fr:tex>P</fr:tex> <fr:em>merely</fr:em> has an upshift. That a negative object <fr:tex>N</fr:tex> has a downshift <fr:link
href="jms-004Z.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004Z">is likewise a proposition</fr:link>, so we can use our assumption that <fr:tex>N</fr:tex> <fr:em>merely</fr:em> has a downshift.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
